definition: "NT-proBNP (N-terminal pro-B-type natriuretic peptide) is an inactive peptide fragment released from the heart — specifically from ventricular cardiomyocytes — in response to increased wall stress from pressure overload or volume overload. The production sequence begins with the synthesis of a precursor protein called pre-proBNP in the heart. Pre-proBNP is cleaved to proBNP, which is then cleaved by the enzyme corin into two fragments: BNP (the biologically active natriuretic hormone) and NT-proBNP (the biologically inactive N-terminal fragment). Both are released into the bloodstream in equimolar amounts during ventricular stress, but NT-proBNP has a much longer plasma half-life (60–120 minutes vs. 20 minutes for BNP) and a higher plasma concentration, making it more sensitive for clinical measurement. NT-proBNP does not have natriuretic hormone activity itself — it is a passive biomarker of the cardiac stress that triggered its production. Its half-life and clearance are primarily renal, which means kidney function substantially influences blood levels."
why_it_matters: "NT-proBNP is the most sensitive and specific single biomarker for heart failure in clinical medicine — its measurement is recommended by major cardiology guidelines (ESC, ACC/AHA) for the diagnosis and monitoring of heart failure with both reduced and preserved ejection fraction. In an acute setting (shortness of breath in the emergency department), NT-proBNP above established age-based cutoffs reliably rules in or rules out acute heart failure with high sensitivity and specificity. In a longevity context, NT-proBNP adds value in three distinct ways: first, as a screening tool for subclinical cardiac dysfunction — elevated NT-proBNP in an asymptomatic person identifies significant cardiac remodeling that warrants investigation before overt symptoms develop; second, as an independent cardiovascular mortality predictor — population studies consistently find that NT-proBNP predicts cardiovascular events and mortality beyond traditional risk factors, including in people with apparently normal cardiac function; and third, as a monitoring tool for known cardiovascular disease — in people with established heart disease or after cardiac events, NT-proBNP trends guide treatment response and risk."

standard_range: "Age-adjusted (age < 75): < 125 pg/mL to rule out heart failure · Age-adjusted (age ≥ 75): < 450 pg/mL · General population optimal: < 75 pg/mL for adults under 55"
